","1500":"1500","1443":"1443","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1388":"1388","1442":"1442","1507":"1507","Cir January 1500":"januar 1500","Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Craigie, Ayrshire, Skotland","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Skotland","Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland":"Kirkcudbrightshire, Skotland","Craige, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"1425–Cir January 1500":"1425–januari 1500","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1415–1472":"1415–1472","1440–1507":"1440–1507","1442–1513":"1442–1513","1388–1443":"1388–1443","1410–1454":"1410–1454","1 NOV 1440":"1 november 1440","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","2 Jul 1472":"2 juli 1472","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1458":"1458","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1443":"1443","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1388":"1388","1442":"1442","1507":"1507","Cir January 1500":"januari 1500","Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Craigie, Ayrshire, Schotland","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Schotland","Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland":"Kirkcudbrightshire, Schotland","Craige, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1425–Cir January 1500":"1425–January 1500","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1415–1472":"1415–1472","1440–1507":"1440–1507","1442–1513":"1442–1513","1388–1443":"1388–1443","1410–1454":"1410–1454","1 NOV 1440":"1 November 1440","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","2 Jul 1472":"2 July 1472","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1458":"1458","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1443":"1443","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1388":"1388","1442":"1442","1507":"1507","Cir January 1500":"January 1500","Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland","Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland":"Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland","Craige, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Dunbar","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Dunbar, a place on the North Sea coast near Edinburgh, named with Gaelic <i>dùn</i> ‘fort’ + <i>barr</i> ‘top, summit’.","History: A family of this name were granted the lands of Dunbar by Malcolm III (1058–1093), and later acquired the earldoms of Dunbar and March. These earldoms were then withdrawn from the family by James I in 1434."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Dunbar Countess of Crawford was born in 1425, in Berwickshire, Scotland, her father, Sir David Dunbar, was 38 and her mother, Lady Margaret Colquhoun, was 15. Sh